[{"location":"","page":"Home","title":"Home","text":"CurrentModule = ITensorGaussianMPS","category":"page"},{"location":"#ITensorGaussianMPS","page":"Home","title":"ITensorGaussianMPS","text":"","category":"section"},{"location":"","page":"Home","title":"Home","text":"Documentation for ITensorGaussianMPS.","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"Home","title":"Home","text":"","category":"page"},{"location":"","page":"Home","title":"Home","text":"Modules = [ITensorGaussianMPS]","category":"page"},{"location":"#ITensors.ITensorMPS.MPS-Tuple{Vector{<:ITensors.Index}, Any, Vector{<:ITensors.ITensor}}","page":"Home","title":"ITensors.ITensorMPS.MPS","text":"MPS(sites::Vector{<:Index}, state, U::Vector{<:ITensor}; kwargs...)\n\nReturn an MPS with site indices sites by applying the circuit U to the starting state state.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"#ITensorGaussianMPS._eigen_gaussian_blocked-Tuple{Any}","page":"Home","title":"ITensorGaussianMPS._eigen_gaussian_blocked","text":"Takes a single-particle Hamiltonian in blocked Dirac format and finds the fermionic transformation U that diagonalizes it\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"#ITensorGaussianMPS.correlation_matrix_to_mps-Tuple{Vector{<:ITensors.Index}, ITensorGaussianMPS.AbstractSymmetry}","page":"Home","title":"ITensorGaussianMPS.correlation_matrix_to_mps","text":"correlation_matrix_to_mps(s::Vector{<:Index}, Λ::AbstractMatrix{ElT};\n                          eigval_cutoff::Float64 = 1e-8,\n                          maxblocksize::Int = size(Λ, 1),\n                          kwargs...)\n\nReturn an approximation to the state represented by the correlation matrix as a matrix product state (MPS).\n\nThe correlation matrix should correspond to a pure state (have all eigenvalues of zero or one).\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"#ITensorGaussianMPS.diag_corr_gaussian-Tuple{AbstractMatrix}","page":"Home","title":"ITensorGaussianMPS.diag_corr_gaussian","text":"Takes a single-particle correlation matrix in interlaced Dirac format and finds the fermionic transformation U that diagonalizes it\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"#ITensorGaussianMPS.diag_corr_gaussian-Tuple{LinearAlgebra.Hermitian}","page":"Home","title":"ITensorGaussianMPS.diag_corr_gaussian","text":"Takes a single-particle correlation matrix in interlaced Dirac format and finds the fermionic transformation U that diagonalizes it\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"#ITensorGaussianMPS.eigen_gaussian-Tuple{Any}","page":"Home","title":"ITensorGaussianMPS.eigen_gaussian","text":"Takes a single-particle Hamiltonian in interlaced Dirac format and finds the complex fermionic transformation U that diagonalizes it.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"#ITensorGaussianMPS.frobenius_distance-Tuple{AbstractMatrix, AbstractMatrix}","page":"Home","title":"ITensorGaussianMPS.frobenius_distance","text":"frobenius_distance(M1::AbstractMatrix, M2::AbstractMatrix)\n\nComputes the Frobenius distance √tr((M1-M2)'*(M1-M2)).\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"#ITensorGaussianMPS.get_gaussian_GS_corr-Tuple{AbstractMatrix}","page":"Home","title":"ITensorGaussianMPS.get_gaussian_GS_corr","text":"Takes a single-particle Hamiltonian in interlaced Dirac format and outputs the ground state correlation matrix (with the input Hamiltonians element type).\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"#ITensorGaussianMPS.givens_rotations-Tuple{ITensorGaussianMPS.ConservesNfParity}","page":"Home","title":"ITensorGaussianMPS.givens_rotations","text":"givensrotations(v0::ConservesNfParity)\n\nFor a vector  julia  v=_v0.data  from a fermionic Gaussian state, return the 4*length(v)-1  real Givens/Boguliobov rotations g and the norm r such that:  ``julia  g * v ≈ r * [n == 2 ? 1 : 0 for n in 1:length(v)] c  withg` being composed of diagonal rotation aligning pairs  of complex numbers in the complex plane, and Givens/Boguliobov Rotations  with real arguments only, acting on the interlaced single-particle space of  annihilation and creation operator coefficients.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"#ITensorGaussianMPS.givens_rotations-Union{Tuple{AbstractVector{ElT}}, Tuple{ElT}} where ElT","page":"Home","title":"ITensorGaussianMPS.givens_rotations","text":"givens_rotations(v::AbstractVector)\n\nFor a vector v, return the length(v)-1 Givens rotations g and the norm r such that:\n\ng * v ≈ r * [n == 1 ? 1 : 0 for n in 1:length(v)]\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"#ITensorGaussianMPS.make_real_if_possible-Tuple{AbstractMatrix, Vector}","page":"Home","title":"ITensorGaussianMPS.make_real_if_possible","text":"Checks if we can make degenerate subspaces of a U0 real by multiplying columns or rows with a phase\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"#ITensorGaussianMPS.make_subspace_real_if_possible-Tuple{AbstractMatrix}","page":"Home","title":"ITensorGaussianMPS.make_subspace_real_if_possible","text":"Checks if we can make a degenerate subspace of the eigenbasis of an operator real by multiplying columns or rows with a phase\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"#ITensorGaussianMPS.order_schur-Tuple{LinearAlgebra.Schur}","page":"Home","title":"ITensorGaussianMPS.order_schur","text":"Schur decomposition of skew-hermitian matrix\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"},{"location":"#ITensorGaussianMPS.slater_determinant_to_mps-Tuple{Vector{<:ITensors.Index}, AbstractMatrix}","page":"Home","title":"ITensorGaussianMPS.slater_determinant_to_mps","text":"slater_determinant_to_mps(s::Vector{<:Index}, Φ::AbstractMatrix; kwargs...)\n\nGiven indices and matrix of orbitals representing a Slater determinant, compute a matrix product state (MPS) approximately having the same correlation matrices as this Slater determinant.\n\nOptional keyword arguments:\n\neigval_cutoff::Float64=1E-8 - cutoff used to adaptively determine the block size (eigenvalues must be closer to 1 or 0 by an amount smaller than this cutoff for their eigenvectors be labeled as \"inactive\" orbitals)\nmaxblocksize::Int - maximum block size used to compute inactive orbitals. Setting this to a smaller value can lead to faster running times and a smaller MPS bond dimension, though the accuracy may be lower.\n\n\n\n\n\n","category":"method"}]
